VIBRIO PARAHAEMOLYTICUS INFECTION - CANADA
******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
[see:
Vibrio parahaemolyticus, shellfish ban - Canada (02) 970817232439
Vibrio parahaemolyticus, shellfish ban - Canada (Vancouver 970804124345]
Date: Fri, 05 Sep 1997 16:55:31 -0400
From: "Robert A. LaBudde" <ral@lcfltd.com>
Excerpted from FSNET (D. Powell, Univ. Guelph):

VIBRIO PARAHAEMOLYTICUS: BRITISH COLUMBIA (UPDATE)
August 29, 1997
Health Canada - Laboratory Centre for Disease Control
Source: BCCDC
Forty-three lab confirmed cases of Vibrio parahaemolyticus infection have
been reported to the BCCDC as of August 21, 1997. Sixty-seven percent are
male. The age range was from 21-79 years, with a mean of 42 years. Food
history was obtained from 39 confirmed cases, of which 34 had eaten oysters
prior to onset of symptoms. Of the remaining 5 confirmed cases, 2 had
consumed crabs, 1 had eaten mussels, 1 shared the same banquet with another
confirmed case (who had eaten raw oysters), and 1 had done extensive
swimming in the ocean 1 day prior to onset of symptoms. There are also 57
clinical cases as of August 21, 1997 - 54 of which had consumed oysters.
Onset dates range from June 19 to August 10, with a peak during the week of
July 28, 1997.
...........................................jw
